example.p:
Therefore, the only possible values of a are 3 and 4. Equation (8.3b) is called the characteristic equation of the recurrence relation.
The fact is that our original recurrence relation is true for any sequence of the form \(S(k) = b_1 3^k + b_24^k\), where \(b_1\) and \(b_2\) are
real numbers. This set of sequences is called the general solution of the recurrence relation. If we didn't have initial conditions for \textit{
S}, we would stop here. The initial conditions make it possible for us to obtain definite values for \(b_1\) and \(b_2\).

\quad \(\left\{
\begin{array}{c}
 S(0)=4 \\
 S(1)=4 \\
\end{array}
\right\}\text{  }\Rightarrow \left\{
\begin{array}{c}
 b_13^0+b_24^0=4 \\
 b_13^1+b_24^1=4 \\
\end{array}
\right\}\text{  }\Rightarrow \left\{
\begin{array}{c}
 b_1+b_2=4 \\
 3b_1+4b_2=4 \\
\end{array}
\right\}\text{  }\)

The solution of this set of simultaneous equations is \(b_1 = 12\) and \(b_2 = -8\) and so the solution is\(S(k) = 12 \cdot 3^k - 8 \cdot 4^k\).

